<section xml:id="sec-from-sets-to-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Moving from sets to functions</title>
<objectives>
<ul>
  <li>
    <p>
      Sets in <m>\lambda^{\lt\lambda}</m> induce functions in the product <m>\prod(\lambda\cap\reg)</m>. 
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Large (in some sense) subsets of <m>\lambda^{\lt\lambda}</m> give rise to large (in a related sense) subsets of <m>\prod(\lambda\cap\reg)</m>
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      The correspondence produces inequalities among cardinal characteristics associated to these structures.
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>  
</objectives>

<p>
  Suppose we have a singular cardinal <m>\lambda</m>.  Given a non-empty subset <m>X</m> of <m>\lambda</m> with <m>|X|\lt\lambda</m>, we can define a function <m>f_X</m> in the product 
<m>\prod(\lambda\cap\reg)</m> by setting
  <me>
    f_X(\theta)=\begin{cases}
    \sup(X\cap\theta)+1 &amp; \text{if }|X|\lt\theta\text{,}\\
    0 &amp; \text{otherwise.}
    \end{cases}
  </me>
</p>
<p>
  Since <m>|X|\lt\lambda</m> it is clear that <m>f_X</m> will be non-zero for all sufficiently large regular cardinals below <m>\lambda</m>, and furthermore if <m>X\subseteq Y</m>
  in <m>[\lambda]^{\lt\lambda}</m> then <m>f_X(\theta)\leq f_Y(\theta)</m> for all regular <m>\theta\lt\lambda</m>.
</p>

<p>
  Suppose now that we have a collection <m>\mathcal{X}</m> that is cofinal in <m>([\lambda]^{\lt\lambda},\subseteq)</m>.  Given a function <m>g\in\prod(\lambda\cap\reg)</m> and a 
  set of regular cardinals <m>A</m> in <m>[\lambda\cap\reg]^{\lt\lambda}</m>, we can choose <m>X\in\mathcal{X}</m> such that 
  <me>
    \ran(g\restr A)\subseteq X.
  </me>
  If <m>A</m> is unbounded in <m>\lambda</m> then <m>g(\theta)\lt f_X(\theta)</m> for all sufficiently large <m>\theta\in A</m>.  Thus, for any subset <m>A</m> of <m>\lambda\cap\reg</m>
  of cardinality less than <m>\lambda</m>, the set of restrictions <m>f_X\restr A</m> for <m>X\in\mathcal{X}</m> is cofinal in the structure <m>\prod A</m> modulo the ideal
  <m>J^{\bd}_\lambda</m> of bounded subsets of <m>\lambda</m>. (Note this will hold automatically for trivial reasons if <m>A</m> is a bounded subset of <m>\lambda</m>).
</p>
</section>